Bob has $2$ sets of all the integers from $1$ through $14$, inclusive. He first picks a number $n$ out of the first set and then chooses a number $m \ne n$ uniformly at random from the second set subject to the following conditions:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item If $n$ is greater than $7$, then $m$ is less than $n$;
        \item If $n$ is less than $7$, then $m$ is greater than $n$;
        \item If $n$ equals $7$, then $m$ is chosen randomly.
    \end{itemize}
    (For example, if Bob chose $12$ on his first pick, he has to choose a number less than $12$ on his second pick.)    If the expected value of the sum of the two numbers he picks can be expressed as $\frac{a}{b}$, where $a$ and $b$ are relatively prime, find $a+b$.
